<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="7"
  data-post-negative="0"
  data-post-positive="7"
  data-post-id="25256045" data-poster-id="283846" id="comment-25256045">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="DerHabbo"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=283846&amp;sid=e8d81635141051048bc0dd167efd8d9f">DerHabbo</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Praetorian</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2013/09/pioneering-bitcoin-hardware-company-to-offer-full-refunds-for-all-chip-orders/?comments=1&post=25256045#comment-25256045" title="2013-09-09T18:40:42-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Mon Sep 09, 2013 5:40 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25255585#p25255585" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">cfarivar</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25255477#p25255477" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">AD</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">&quot;bitcoins get harder to mine over time.&quot;<br /><br />This is not true. The difficulty dynamically adjusts in both directions depending on if more mining power comes online or goes offline. From Dec '12 to Feb '13 the difficulty decreased.</div><br /><br />Is this not generally the entire principle of bitcoin, though?</div><br /><br />I'd say Cyrus's assessment that the value goes down over time will always be accurate. While difficulty swings based on hash rates (which is to say, the total hashing speed of the entire bitcoin network) the release, or AMOUNT of coins generated will continue to drop. You will never again receive 50 BTC for a single cracked block. Within a few years, you will never again receive 25 BTC. Those releases are lost with time. Eventually, it'll stop releasing altogether, and tx payments will be the only payment miners who crack a block will receive.<br /><br />Time is money in BTC, and the hashing time lost to these delays is costing early adopters in the form of write-down losses, and it's all the ASIC or FPGA companies fault. I suppose it's understandable if they're bitter enough that a simple refund no longer cuts it. Then again, what fun would high risk investments be without the high risk part?
      
    </div>
    <footer>
