  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="TeknoKid"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=75897&amp;sid=e8d81635141051048bc0dd167efd8d9f">TeknoKid</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Praetorian</span><a class="subscriber" href="/subscriptions/">et Subscriptor</a>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2013/09/pioneering-bitcoin-hardware-company-to-offer-full-refunds-for-all-chip-orders/?comments=1&post=25257967#comment-25257967" title="2013-09-10T01:10:22-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Tue Sep 10, 2013 12:10 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25257085#p25257085" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">melgross</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">From my understanding of mining of Bitcoin is that it's like finding Prime Numbers. The more that are found, the harder it is to find more. There is one difference if what I read is correct. While there is no end to Prime Numbers, there is a fixed number of Bitcoins. Once they are all found, there aren't any more.<br /><br />I can't verify what I just said, because I can't find the bookmark from where I read it. But if true, it does put a different light on things.</div><br /><br />It's really simple actually.  The goal is to have one transaction every 10 minutes. If the network processing power increases (or decreases) such that transactions are occurring faster (or slower) the difficulty is adjusted to bring the transaction rate back to one every 10 minutes.<br /><br />With all the ASICS coming online the difficulty has been going up.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
