<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="-2"
  data-post-negative="-5"
  data-post-positive="3"
  data-post-id="25258435" data-poster-id="368199" id="comment-25258435">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="docbain"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=368199&amp;sid=e8d81635141051048bc0dd167efd8d9f">docbain</a></span><span class="rank">Wise, Aged Ars Veteran</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2013/09/pioneering-bitcoin-hardware-company-to-offer-full-refunds-for-all-chip-orders/?comments=1&post=25258435#comment-25258435" title="2013-09-10T04:47:18-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Tue Sep 10, 2013 3:47 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25258099#p25258099" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">nibb</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25257355#p25257355" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">PyWrite</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Traditional money represent value, past and future. Bitcoins represent waste. Pure waste. In that sense, they are anti-money.</div><br /><br />And papers money is not? If you go by that rule, only true gold would not be waste as exchange. Currently money has also value of absolutely nothing except some law printed on the bill.<br /></div><br /><br />Every form of money is wasteful to some extent. Paper money takes time and effort to manufacture - but making and printing paper is pretty cheap. Bitcoin is much less efficient - mining Bitcoin uses about 1000 Megawatt hours per day. There is no conceptual reason why the Bitcoin concept required the algorithm for creating money to be competitively cracking SHA hashes. The coins could've just been defined as a numbered sequence and generated in less than a second on a standard PC, as opposed to over several years on many PCs and other bits of hardware. The end effect would've been the same. OTOH, competitive mining was a good form of marketing to draw people in who hoped to get rich.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
