<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="-1"
  data-post-negative="-2"
  data-post-positive="1"
  data-post-id="25258747" data-poster-id="375765" id="comment-25258747">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="rdx"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=375765&amp;sid=e8d81635141051048bc0dd167efd8d9f">rdx</a></span><span class="rank">Wise, Aged Ars Veteran</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2013/09/pioneering-bitcoin-hardware-company-to-offer-full-refunds-for-all-chip-orders/?comments=1&post=25258747#comment-25258747" title="2013-09-10T07:05:08-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Tue Sep 10, 2013 6:05 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25258435#p25258435" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">docbain</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25258099#p25258099" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">nibb</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25257355#p25257355" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">PyWrite</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Traditional money represent value, past and future. Bitcoins represent waste. Pure waste. In that sense, they are anti-money.</div><br /><br />And papers money is not? If you go by that rule, only true gold would not be waste as exchange. Currently money has also value of absolutely nothing except some law printed on the bill.<br /></div><br /><br />Every form of money is wasteful to some extent. Paper money takes time and effort to manufacture - but making and printing paper is pretty cheap. Bitcoin is much less efficient - mining Bitcoin uses about 1000 Megawatt hours per day. There is no conceptual reason why the Bitcoin concept required the algorithm for creating money to be competitively cracking SHA hashes. The coins could've just been defined as a numbered sequence and generated in less than a second on a standard PC, as opposed to over several years on many PCs and other bits of hardware. The end effect would've been the same. OTOH, competitive mining was a good form of marketing to draw people in who hoped to get rich.</div><br /><br />There are no actual coins to number in BtC and getting brand new coins is basically just a by-product of mining. In Bitcoin there are only records in the global ledger - &quot;Account X sent N coins to account Y&quot; (mined coins are simply &quot;There are now X coins in account Y&quot;).<br /><br />Clients just send and receive new records, miners work on actually committing them. Hashing is basically DoS protection so a malicious party wouldn't overwhelm the net with crafted blocks.<br /><br />Technically Bitcoin's quite nice and works great for money transfers, nothing wrong with SHA there - it's long term economical planning that's lacking from design.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
